// frame.su — the first Yantra GUI frame, computed ON THE SUBSTRATE.
//
// pixel(x, y) returns the brightness of one pixel, for centred coordinates
// x, y in [-1, 1]:
//
//     brightness = 1 - x^2 - y^2
//
// which is 1 at the centre and falls off radially to the edges — a glow. Every
// arithmetic step (x*x, the subtractions) runs on the Sutra substrate; make_real
// lifts the result onto the real axis so the host can read it with real().
//
// The host (apps/gui/window.py) walks the pixel grid, maps each pixel to centred
// coordinates, calls pixel(x, y) on the substrate, then clamps + colour-maps +
// displays. The substrate computes the image FIELD; the host only assembles the
// grid and paints the window — the same host-is-I/O split as the calculator
// (host reads/writes, the substrate computes the value).
//
// This is the first GUI proof of concept. The fuller form Emma described — a
// single returned vector "reorganised" into pixels by a reverse-CNN-style
// decoder — is the next step (planning/24-first-gui.md); this per-pixel field is
// the smallest honest version that puts substrate-computed pixels on a screen.
function vector pixel(scalar x, scalar y) {
    return make_real(1.0 - x * x - y * y);
}

function vector main() { return pixel(0.0, 0.0); }
